The paper proposes a novel network architecture for video-based person re-identification, which involves learning appearance representation and motion context from a collection of adjacent frames. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves deep learning techniques, which are commonly used in the machine learning (cs.MM) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also addresses the problem of video surveillance, which is related to the computer security and cryptography (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves extensive experiments on benchmark datasets, which suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
